04352nam a22006975i 9780231517911DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2008002981  a97802315179117 a10.7312/inou146162doi  a(DE-B1597)458964  a(OCoLC)979969458  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPL830.N63bA79313 2008 7aLIT0080002bisacsh04a895.6/351 aYasushi, Inoue, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Blue Wolf :bA Novel of the Life of Chinggis Khan /cInoue Yasushi. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWeatherhead Books on Asia00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTranslator’s Note -- tMap -- t1. Earliest Years -- t2. The Merkid Massacre -- t3. Overlordship on the Mongolian Plateau -- t4. Temüjin Becomes Chinggis Khan -- t5. Attack on the Jin -- t6. Fall of the Jin Dynasty -- t7. The Destruction of Khorazm -- t8. Return to Mount Burqan -- tAuthor’s Afterword (1960) -- tDramatis Personae -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the world's most ruthless warriors, Chinggis Khan conquered nearly all of Asia in the twelfth and thirteenth centuries, transforming the scattered and impoverished Mongols into an exceptionally proud and powerful nation. In this riveting and thoroughly researched portrait, Japan's celebrated epic novelist drives at the root of the khan's great desires and insatiable appetite for supremacy.Beginning with his birth in 1162, The Blue Wolf follows the crucial alliances that led to Chinggis Khan's great campaigns in North China, Bukhara, and Samarkand, as well as the state of Khorazm. The khan was obsessed with his ancestry, not knowing whether he was the descendent of the blue wolf (mythical progenitor of the Mongols and the noble Borjigin line) or merely the bastard son of a Merkid tribesman. For Inoue Yasushi, Chinggis's ancestral anxiety lies at the center of his relentless push for empire. He struggled with his paternity as intensely as he fought his battles, and his victories stood as proof that the brave warrior was a true Mongol. The question of paternity also formed the largest wedge between Chinggis and his eldest son, Jochi, a boy born in captivity and of similarly questionable heritage. Hailed for its sophistication and rich imagining of a remote world, The Blue Wolf puts a human cast on a legendary force that changed Asia and the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh1 aFogel, Joshua.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/inou1461640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231517911423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231517911/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK